Classifying sentiment of 1 Million Tweets using LSTM & Pre-trained Glove Embeddings in Tensorflow¶

Author: Aditya Patel

Dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/kazanova/sentiment140
Techniques used: LSTM, Transfer Learning Pre-trained Glove Embeddings in Tensorflow

Step 1: Preprocessing Dataset

 Dataset is a .csv file. Extracted text strings and labels (i.e. sentiment values) from it. Created 2 lists, one is a list of sentences where each sentence is a long string and 2nd list is a list of labels i.e. target values. The original labels were 0 and 4 indicating -ve and +ve sentiment. These will be converted into 0 and 1 for binary classification

Step 2: Create Corpus dictionary e.g. corpus['please'] = 234

 Instantiate Keras Tokenizer and fit it on the list of 1 Million sentences/tweets created above. Thus, 1 Million tweets are tokenized. The number of tokens is around 1/2 million. Tokenization means converting words into numbers. Then I pad them so that all tweets have 30 words to maintain consisten in order to feed into a neural network.
Step 3: Create embedding matrix weights to feed into Neural Net.

Import Pre-trained GloVe embeddings and create a embedding matrix of size (vocab_size, 100). Vocab size is 503348. Note this is a 100 dimension version of GloVe. GloVe embeddings come in a .txt text file. Each word is a vector of 100 elements and this has been trained using large dataset. For each word in my training sentence, I'll search for its vector in GloVe embeddings dictionary. This matrix will be 503348 x 100. These are pre-trained weights and will be passed into neural net and will be frozen i.e. non-trainable
Step 4: Create a Neural Net

 1st layer will be Embedding. I'm feeding a tweet to it. Tweet has 30 words i.e. 30 sequence of numbers. Each word (i.e. its number) will be converted into a vector of dimension 100. So the o/p of the embedding layer will be 30 x 100. Next will be Dropout, Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, LSTM and output layer will be Dense with 1 neuron and sigmoud output since it's binary classification
Step 5: Train neural net and see performance on test set

import tensorflow as tf
import csv, random, numpy as np, pandas as pd

from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.text import Tokenizer
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, LSTM, Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, Dropout, Embedding

Dimension of embedding/feature must be 100 as i'm using GloVe embedding pre-trained weights. This could be 20 or 30 or 4 or 500, if i had chosen to train them. But since i am using ready made pretrained weights, i'll wanna have dimension of each word to be a vector of dimension 100

In [2]:
#     --------hyperparameters---------
embedding_dim = 100
max_length = 30         # ek tweet/sentence ma 30 words max
trunc_type='post'       # lamba sentence ne kapva
padding_type='post'     # short sentence ne extend kar after its end
oov_tok = "???"         # any symbol can be used instead of ??? as long as it is unique
training_size=int(1e6)  # indicates how many tweets to train on i.e form a corpus on
test_portion=0.4        # 40% is good test of generalizability

Note above 40% of tweets are unseen which is a good test of robustness and generalizability

num_sentences = 0

With the way the .csv dataset is, the first few hundred thousand reviews are all negative i.e. 0, so must shuffle them

In [5]:
df = df.sample(frac=1)     # to shuffle
sentences = df['text'].tolist()[0:training_size]
labels = df['sentiment'].tolist()[0:training_size]
num_sentences = len(sentences)
labels = [1 if i ==4 else 0 for i in labels]      # super important to convert label 4 to 1. Binary classifier does not recognize 4

tokenizer = Tokenizer(oov_token=oov_tok)
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(sentences)            # Fit tokenizer on list of 1 Million tweets

word_index = tokenizer.word_index   # this creates a dictionary e.g. word_index['please'] = 235
vocab_size=len(word_index)          # this is around 500K tokens

sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(sentences)
padded = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=max_length, padding=padding_type, truncating=trunc_type)

split = int(test_portion * training_size)

test_sequences = padded[0:split]                 # 0 to 400K
test_labels = labels[0:split]                    # 400K to 1 Million
training_sequences = padded[split:training_size] 
training_labels = labels[split:training_size]

Step 3¶

In [6]:
"""Note this is the 100 dimension version of GloVe from Stanford. 
So "each" word is a vector [_,_,_,..100 elements]"""

embeddings_dictionary= {}
with open('glove.6B.100d.txt') as f:
    for line in f.readlines():
        values = line.split()
        word = values[0]
        vector = np.array(values[1:], dtype = float)   # Each vector has dimension 100
        embeddings_dictionary[word] = vector 

embeddings_matrix = np.zeros((vocab_size+1, embedding_dim))  # vocab_size+1 'cos numbers in vocab start from 1 not 0
for word, number in word_index.items():
    embedding_vector = embeddings_dictionary.get(word);
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        embeddings_matrix[number] = embedding_vector

Step 4¶

In [7]:
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    Embedding(vocab_size+1,          # this number of units
              embedding_dim,         # this is exactly like kernel size 
              input_length=max_length, 
              weights=[embeddings_matrix], 
              trainable=False),
    Dropout(0.2),
    Conv1D(64, 5, activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling1D(pool_size=4),
    LSTM(64),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',optimizer='adam',metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

num_epochs = 10

X_train= training_sequences
y_train = np.array(training_labels)
X_test = test_sequences
y_test = np.array(test_labels)

history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=num_epochs, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), verbose=2)

print("Training Complete")
